# ACE Project Memory

You have access to a structured project backlog via REST API. After completing work,
you MUST record what you did by creating or updating project memory items.

## Human actor (MANDATORY)

The person using DevLay for this run is: **sarath@harmonyflow.ai**

- Set **author** to this name (or their email, if that is their identity in ACE).
- Put the same in **contributors** for work they did, plus any other humans.
- **Never** use the literal `cursor-agent`, the word `Cursor` as a stand-in, any CLI
  or model name, or "the agent" for **author** or as the only contributor. The "queue" is
  an internal engine concept — the human in DevLay is who you attribute.

## Git branch (for `branch` / `branches` fields)

Run `git branch --show-current` and use **that** exact string. Do not invent a branch name.
If the repository still uses `master` as the current branch, record `master`. If the default
is `main`, you will see `main`. (Renaming the default branch in git is a human/CI concern.)

## API Reference (all endpoints relative to the engine at http://localhost:3002)

### Full backlog
GET /api/project-memory

### Epics (large initiatives)
GET    /api/project-memory/epics
POST   /api/project-memory/epics           { title, description, author, contributors?, status?, branches? }
GET    /api/project-memory/epics/:id
PUT    /api/project-memory/epics/:id        { title?, description?, status?, author?, contributors?, branches? }
DELETE /api/project-memory/epics/:id

### Stories (feature-level work)
GET    /api/project-memory/stories          ?epic_id=<filter>
POST   /api/project-memory/stories          { title, description, author, contributors?, epic_id?, status?, branches?, tested? }
GET    /api/project-memory/stories/:id
PUT    /api/project-memory/stories/:id      { title?, description?, status?, author?, contributors?, epic_id?, branches?, tested? }
DELETE /api/project-memory/stories/:id

### Tasks (smallest unit of work)
GET    /api/project-memory/tasks            ?story_id=<filter>
POST   /api/project-memory/tasks            { title, description, author, contributors?, story_id?, status?, branch?, tested?, files_changed?, commit_hash?, queue_id?, thread_id? }
PUT    /api/project-memory/tasks/:id        { title?, description?, status?, author?, contributors?, branch?, tested?, files_changed?, commit_hash? }
DELETE /api/project-memory/tasks/:id

### Branch queries
GET /api/project-memory/branches/:branch

### Search
GET /api/project-memory/search?q=<query>

### Discussion channels
POST /api/project-memory/discuss/:item_type/:item_id  (idempotent - creates or returns existing discussion channel)

## Fields (API body)

- **author**: The primary **human** owner — must match the Human actor section above, not a bot/CLI name.
- **contributors**: Human contributors for this item; same rule as **author** when the human did the work.
- **discussion_channel_id**: (read-only) Set automatically when a discussion is started for an item.

## Status values
backlog, in_progress, done, cancelled

## Workflow

1. Before starting, run `curl -s http://localhost:3002/api/project-memory` to see existing work items.
2. After completing your work, create a Task for each distinct change (include files_changed, branch, your queue_id).
3. If this task is part of a larger feature, create or update a Story to group related Tasks.
4. If there is a larger initiative, create or link to an Epic.
5. Set status to "done" for completed items and "in_progress" for ongoing work.
6. For **branch** / **branches**: use the real branch from `git branch --show-current` (see Git branch section). Do not invent names.
7. For **author** and **contributors**: use the Human actor / humans only — not `cursor-agent` or the queue label.
